{"questionId":"27640","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The quadratic function&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math>&nbsp;is defined by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>p</mi></math>&nbsp;where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>The graph of a quadratic function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> has its vertex at the point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and it intersects&nbsp;the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>. Find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>k</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>correct substitution of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;into&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p>\n<p>correct substitution of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> The first two A marks are independent.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27640","referenceCode":"22N.1.SL.TZ0.7a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The graph of a quadratic function f has its vertex at the point (3, 2) and it intersects the x-axis at x=5. Find f in the form f(x)=a(x-h)2+k.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Quadratic function"],"membe